# GOAL

Remove the architecture smell: Insufficient Modularization from the TARGET CLASS.

For this MVP, prefer behavior-preserving refactorings. API-preserving refactorings are preferred when they are sufficient, but controlled API changes are allowed when they are necessary to remove the smell and can be handled within the target class, newly extracted classes, and mechanically added related tests.

Allowed strategy:
- Extract cohesive private methods and helper logic into new classes.
- Move private helper methods when this reduces the complexity or size of the target class.
- Avoid moving public methods. Move public methods only when they clearly belong to the extracted responsibility, behavior is preserved, and all required updates remain within the block.
- Do not change public API unless the changed member belongs to the target class responsibility being extracted and all required updates are limited to files in the block.
- Prefer refactorings whose production call-site updates are limited to the target class and newly created classes.
- Plan only production-code refactorings. Do not include src/test files, UPDATE_TESTS operations, or test-specific changes. Related tests will be added by a deterministic post-processing step.

# ALLOWED OPS

EXTRACT_CLASS, EXTRACT_INTERFACE, MOVE_METHOD, MOVE_FIELD, INTRODUCE_FACADE, DEPENDENCY_INVERSION, REPLACE_DEPENDENCY, CREATE_PACKAGE, MOVE_CLASS, ADD_OR_UPDATE_IMPORTS, UPDATE_CALL_SITES

Use NO_OP only when no safe refactoring plan can be produced at all.
Do not include NO_OP inside a block that already contains real refactoring operations.
Do not use NO_OP as a placeholder, filler, or block-size adjustment.

# CONSTRAINTS

1. Reference only packages, classes, methods, and fields present in the input.
2. Each block must be small and independently compilable.
3. New classes must be placed in the same package as the target class unless the input clearly justifies otherwise.
4. Do not create compatibility wrappers.
5. Keep blocks small: 3–8 ops per block.

